    <h1>Car win&#xAD;dow tint&#xAD;ing</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201110/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-10"><time>2020-11-10</time></a>
        - <span>CLASSIFIED&#xAD;S</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Car win­dow films or tints pro­vide many ben­e­fits to car own­ers.</p>
    <p>Some win­dow films are made to re­flect sun rays, re­duc­ing the heat build-up in cars.</p>
    <p>Some are lay­ered with UV-block­ing coat­ing to pro­tect the driv­ers from harm­ful ef­fects of the sun’s UV rays. Oth­ers sim­ply do its job to re­duce glare from the sun.</p>
    <p>DON’T BREAK THE LAW</p>
    <p>Ap­ply­ing tints and films to your car win­dows con­sti­tutes a ve­hi­cle mod­i­fi­ca­tion. Take great care not to flout the laws by us­ing unau­tho­rised tints and films that are too dark or made of re­flec­tive ma­te­ri­als.</p>


